<ArticleLayout
  title="Kitchen Bench Space: What to Clear Before Buying More Storage"
  description="Before buying more kitchen storage, check what is taking up bench space, which appliances earn their place, and whether clearing, grouping or relocating items will help first."
  category="Kitchen"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="7 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/kitchen.webp"
  imageAlt="A warm kitchen with clear bench space, timber cabinetry and green accents"
>
  <p>
    Kitchen bench space is easy to lose.
  </p>
  <p>
    A coffee machine stays out. The air fryer never quite goes away. Mail lands near the fruit
    bowl. A dish rack takes over one side of the sink. Cooking oil, utensils, vitamins,
    lunchboxes, appliances and containers slowly claim space until there is nowhere
    comfortable to prepare food.
  </p>
  <p>
    When that happens, it can be tempting to buy more storage. A trolley, rack, shelf, stand
    or organiser may help in some kitchens. But before adding another product, it is worth
    checking what is already using the bench and whether anything can be cleared, grouped or
    moved.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide explains what to clear before buying more kitchen storage, especially for
    Australian homes, rentals, apartments and smaller kitchens.
  </p>
  <p>
    For broader kitchen storage planning, see our main guide:
    <a href="/guides/best-kitchen-storage-ideas-small-australian-homes/">Kitchen Storage: What to Measure and Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with the real bench space problem</h2>
  <p>
    Bench clutter can come from several different problems.
  </p>
  <p>It may be caused by:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Too many appliances kept out.</li>
    <li>Poor pantry storage.</li>
    <li>Drawers that are too full.</li>
    <li>No clear place for lunchboxes.</li>
    <li>Dishes waiting to dry.</li>
    <li>Cleaning products near the sink.</li>
    <li>Mail, keys or household items landing in the kitchen.</li>
    <li>Cooking oils and seasonings left out.</li>
    <li>Fruit bowls, vitamins or supplements taking up space.</li>
    <li>Items stored on the bench because cupboards are hard to access.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Different problems need different solutions.
  </p>
  <p>
    If appliances are the issue, the answer may be appliance storage. If pantry overflow is
    the issue, pantry grouping may help. If utensils are scattered across the bench, drawer
    organisation may be the better starting point.
  </p>
  <p>
    The first question is not "What storage product should I buy?" The first question is "What
    keeps ending up on the bench, and why?"
  </p>

  <h2>Decide what the bench needs to do</h2>
  <p>
    A kitchen bench is working space.
  </p>
  <p>It may need to support:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Food preparation.</li>
    <li>Cooking.</li>
    <li>Packing lunches.</li>
    <li>Making coffee or tea.</li>
    <li>Serving meals.</li>
    <li>Washing up.</li>
    <li>Unloading groceries.</li>
    <li>Sorting school or work items.</li>
    <li>Cooling baked food.</li>
    <li>Using small appliances.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If the bench is full of stored items, it cannot do these jobs properly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying more storage, choose the main job for each bench area.
  </p>
  <p>For example:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>One section for food preparation.</li>
    <li>One small zone for coffee or tea.</li>
    <li>One area near the sink for washing up.</li>
    <li>One temporary area for lunchbox packing.</li>
    <li>One clear landing space for groceries.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Not every kitchen has room for all of these zones. In smaller kitchens, the priority
    should usually be keeping at least one clear preparation area available.
  </p>

  <h2>Clear appliances that do not earn bench space</h2>
  <p>
    Small appliances are one of the biggest causes of lost bench space.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some appliances are worth keeping out because they are used daily. Others stay out because
    they are too awkward to store, not because they are actually used often.
  </p>
  <p>Look at every appliance on the bench and ask:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Is this used daily?</li>
    <li>Is it used several times a week?</li>
    <li>Is it too heavy to move safely?</li>
    <li>Does it need to stay plugged in?</li>
    <li>Does it block preparation space?</li>
    <li>Does it duplicate another appliance?</li>
    <li>Would I still use it if it lived in a cupboard?</li>
    <li>Is it there because there is no storage plan?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Daily-use appliances may deserve bench space. Occasional appliances usually need a clear
    storage location.
  </p>
  <p>
    If there is no realistic place to store an appliance, that is a storage problem worth
    solving. But if the appliance is rarely used, it may be better to remove it before buying
    storage around it.
  </p>
  <p>
    For more detail, see:
    <a href="/guides/small-kitchen-appliances-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">Small Kitchen Appliances: What to Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Move pantry overflow back into the pantry</h2>
  <p>
    Bench clutter often starts when pantry items do not have a clear place.
  </p>
  <p>Common examples include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Bread.</li>
    <li>Cereal boxes.</li>
    <li>Snacks.</li>
    <li>Tea and coffee.</li>
    <li>Vitamins.</li>
    <li>Sauces.</li>
    <li>Cooking oils.</li>
    <li>Spice jars.</li>
    <li>Unopened grocery items.</li>
    <li>Lunchbox snacks.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Some of these may be reasonable to keep out if they are used constantly. But if the bench
    is becoming a backup pantry, the pantry probably needs attention first.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying bench storage, check whether pantry items can be grouped better.
  </p>
  <p>Useful pantry fixes may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Grouping breakfast items.</li>
    <li>Creating a snack basket.</li>
    <li>Using clear bins for small packets.</li>
    <li>Adjusting shelf height.</li>
    <li>Removing expired food.</li>
    <li>Moving bulk items away from daily-use shelves.</li>
    <li>Keeping oils and sauces together.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For pantry-specific planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/pantry-storage-what-to-measure-before-buying-organisers/">Pantry Storage: What to Measure Before Buying Organisers</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Check whether drawers are forcing items onto the bench</h2>
  <p>
    Sometimes items live on the bench because drawers are full.
  </p>
  <p>
    Utensils, wraps, clips, lunchbox parts, tea towels, measuring spoons and small tools often
    end up on the bench when drawer storage is crowded or unclear.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a bench-top organiser, check the nearby drawers.</p>
  <p>Ask:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Is this drawer doing too many jobs?</li>
    <li>Are duplicate tools taking up space?</li>
    <li>Are long utensils tangled together?</li>
    <li>Are small items getting lost?</li>
    <li>Could a drawer divider solve the issue?</li>
    <li>Could some items move to a less-used drawer?</li>
    <li>Are unused gadgets taking up prime space?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A bench-top utensil holder may help if the tools are used daily and the bench has room.
    But if the bench is already tight, improving the drawer may be better.
  </p>
  <p>
    For drawer-specific planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/kitchen-drawer-storage-what-to-measure-before-buying-organisers/">Kitchen Drawer Storage: What to Measure Before Buying Organisers</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep the sink area under control</h2>
  <p>
    The area around the sink can take over the bench quickly.
  </p>
  <p>Common sink-area clutter includes:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Dish racks.</li>
    <li>Sponges.</li>
    <li>Dishwashing liquid.</li>
    <li>Cleaning sprays.</li>
    <li>Cloths.</li>
    <li>Gloves.</li>
    <li>Bottle brushes.</li>
    <li>Dishwasher tablets.</li>
    <li>Drying bottles.</li>
    <li>Loose containers and lids.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Some of this needs to be close to the sink. But it does not all need to spread across the
    bench.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying more sink storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Whether the dish rack is too large.</li>
    <li>Whether drying items can be put away sooner.</li>
    <li>Whether cleaning products can move under the sink.</li>
    <li>Whether sponges and brushes need a smaller holder.</li>
    <li>Whether the area is hard to wipe down.</li>
    <li>Whether the bench is being used as long-term drying storage.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Under-sink storage may help, but only if pipes, moisture and access are checked first.
  </p>
  <p>
    For more detail, see:
    <a href="/guides/under-sink-kitchen-storage-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">Under-Sink Kitchen Storage: What to Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Watch for non-kitchen clutter</h2>
  <p>
    The kitchen bench often becomes a household landing zone.
  </p>
  <p>Items may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Mail.</li>
    <li>Receipts.</li>
    <li>Keys.</li>
    <li>Sunglasses.</li>
    <li>Chargers.</li>
    <li>School notes.</li>
    <li>Work items.</li>
    <li>Small tools.</li>
    <li>Medicines.</li>
    <li>Toys.</li>
    <li>Bags.</li>
    <li>Random items waiting to be moved.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This type of clutter is not usually solved by kitchen storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    It may need a small household drop zone somewhere else, such as an entry table, drawer,
    basket, office tray or hallway shelf.
  </p>
  <p>
    If non-kitchen items keep landing on the bench, adding more kitchen organisers may only
    make the problem look more permanent.
  </p>

  <h2>Be careful with bench-top organisers</h2>
  <p>
    Bench-top organisers can be useful, but they also take up working space.
  </p>
  <p>They may help with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Coffee and tea supplies.</li>
    <li>Daily cooking oils.</li>
    <li>Utensils used every day.</li>
    <li>Fruit.</li>
    <li>Dishwashing items.</li>
    <li>Frequently used spices.</li>
    <li>Lunchbox packing.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    They are less useful when they become a place for random overflow.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a bench-top organiser, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>How much bench depth it will use.</li>
    <li>Whether it blocks preparation space.</li>
    <li>Whether it is easy to clean around.</li>
    <li>Whether it creates visual clutter.</li>
    <li>Whether it holds items used daily.</li>
    <li>Whether the items could live in a drawer, cupboard or pantry instead.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A clear bench is often more useful than a neatly organised crowded bench.
  </p>

  <h2>Think carefully before adding a trolley</h2>
  <p>
    A kitchen trolley can help in some homes, especially rentals and small kitchens with
    limited cupboard space.
  </p>
  <p>
    But it can also block movement and become another clutter surface.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a trolley, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Floor space.</li>
    <li>Walkway width.</li>
    <li>Fridge door swing.</li>
    <li>Oven door clearance.</li>
    <li>Dishwasher door clearance.</li>
    <li>Cupboard door clearance.</li>
    <li>Trolley height.</li>
    <li>Trolley depth.</li>
    <li>Whether it can be cleaned around easily.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A trolley should solve a specific problem, such as storing daily appliances, lunchbox
    items, pantry overflow or tea and coffee supplies.
  </p>
  <p>
    If it simply becomes another place to put things down, it may make the kitchen feel more
    crowded.
  </p>
  <p>
    For rental kitchens, make sure any freestanding storage can move with you and does not
    rely on permanent changes. See:
    <a href="/guides/renter-friendly-kitchen-storage-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">Renter-Friendly Kitchen Storage: What to Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Common bench space mistakes</h2>
  <p>
    Kitchen bench space can disappear when storage products are added too quickly.
  </p>
  <p>Common mistakes include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Keeping rarely used appliances on the bench.</li>
    <li>Buying a trolley without measuring walkways.</li>
    <li>Using the bench as pantry overflow.</li>
    <li>Keeping too many utensils in bench-top holders.</li>
    <li>Letting dishes dry on the bench for too long.</li>
    <li>Storing non-kitchen items in the kitchen.</li>
    <li>Choosing large organisers for small benches.</li>
    <li>Buying more storage before clearing duplicates.</li>
    <li>Ignoring nearby drawers and cupboards.</li>
    <li>Keeping items out because they do not have a home.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The goal is not to display everything neatly. The goal is to preserve working space.
  </p>

  <h2>When not to buy more storage yet</h2>
  <p>
    You may not need more storage yet if the bench is crowded because of habits or excess
    items.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, check whether the bench contains:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Appliances used rarely.</li>
    <li>Pantry items that could be grouped elsewhere.</li>
    <li>Dishes that need putting away.</li>
    <li>Duplicate utensils.</li>
    <li>Cleaning products that belong under the sink.</li>
    <li>Containers without lids.</li>
    <li>Non-kitchen household items.</li>
    <li>Items waiting to be thrown out, donated or moved.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If clearing these items improves the bench, more storage may not be needed.
  </p>
  <p>
    In many kitchens, the best upgrade is not another organiser. It is a clear, usable section
    of bench that stays available for food preparation.
  </p>

  <h2>Simple bench space checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying more kitchen storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>What keeps ending up on the bench?</li>
    <li>Does each bench area have a clear job?</li>
    <li>Which appliances are used daily?</li>
    <li>Which appliances could be stored away?</li>
    <li>Is pantry overflow causing clutter?</li>
    <li>Are drawers too full to use properly?</li>
    <li>Are sink items taking over the bench?</li>
    <li>Are non-kitchen items landing here?</li>
    <li>Would a trolley block movement?</li>
    <li>Would a bench-top organiser reduce working space?</li>
    <li>Would clearing duplicates solve the problem first?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Kitchen bench space is valuable because it is working space.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying another organiser, shelf or trolley, clear what does not need to be there
    and protect at least one practical area for preparing food.
  </p>

